Tafseer:
Do they have feet by which they walk? Or do they have hands by which they strike? Or do they have eyes by which they see? Or do they have ears by which they hear? Say, [O Muhammad], 'Invoke your partners and then scheme against me and do not give me respite.' 

The refutation of idol-worship from its manifest and hidden aspects—both: Idol-worship is composed of two parts. One are those 'essences' (dhawat) which the idol-worshippers—according to their assumption—believe to be partners in divinity and declare them to be 'Ilah' (god). Second are those images of stone and gold or silver which they cast or carve as the bodies and molds of those essences, and they hold the assumption that their assumed deities indwell/incarnate within these manifestations, and the worship of these manifestations is the medium and means for the worship of those gods. In terms of theory, the supporters of idol-worship say this very thing in its support; but practically it happens that the commoners consider everything to be these very images before which they prostrate and present offerings and sacrifice. Here, the Quran has refuted idol-worship by placing both its aspects in front. In the verses above, He refuted while keeping the essences in view; now He is refuting while keeping their manifestations in view—that 'look, the hands and feet, ears, eyes you have made for them are all showy and for display; they cannot even remove a fly from their own face and they cannot even protect the milk and halwa placed in front of them from dogs and cats; so how will they be able to give you any help—you who have made them your refuge and sanctuary and Protector and Taskmaster.' 

This same reality has been clarified in the Psalms in these words: 
'Their idols are silver and gold, 
Even the handiwork of man. 
They have mouths, but they speak not; 
Eyes have they, but they see not; 
They have ears, but they hear not; 
Noses have they, but they smell not; 
They have hands, but they handle not; 
Feet have they, but they walk not; 
Neither speak they through their throat. 
They that make them are like unto them; 
So is every one that trusteth in them.' (Psalms 115:3–8). 

'Say, Invoke your partners and then scheme against me and do not give me respite.' This is the response to the threats of the polytheists—that 'you frighten me with these lifeless and motionless images, that as a result of their condemnation and opposition, their wrath will ignite against me.' If you hold this assumption, then you call all your these goddesses and gods for your help and carry out whatever scheme you can carry out against me—do not show even a bit of favor and do not give me respite for even a single day.
